{"questionId":"22878","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Arianne plays a game of darts.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/0895245a633b00bd261cccdb1b293a73688d8edb.png\"></p>\n<p>The distance that her darts land from the centre, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>O</mtext></math>, of the board can be modelled by a normal distribution with mean <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math> and standard deviation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Each of Arianne’s throws is independent of her previous throws.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the probability that Arianne throws two consecutive darts that land more than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>O</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><mtext>P</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00228</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00228391</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22878","referenceCode":"21N.2.SL.TZ0.5b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the probability that Arianne throws two consecutive darts that land more than 15 cm from O.","paper":"2","level":"SL","quest